1. First run ADF tests and conclude: Is this series stationary?

Stationary means: constant mean; constant variance; doesn't wander indefinitely.

Run ADF twice — once for stock A and once for stock B — on the full 1-year price series.
Interpretation: p < 0.05 = stationary; p > 0.05 = non-stationary.
If non-stationary: give it a check mark ✓ (this is required for cointegration).
If stationary: give it a question mark ? (unexpected for raw prices).


2. Second, run the Engle-Granger cointegration test per quarter.

The past 1 year of daily price data is divided into 4 equal quarterly windows:
  Q1 = oldest quarter, Q2, Q3, Q4 = most recent quarter (~63 trading days each).

For each quarter, run Engle-Granger in BOTH directions:

Direction A→B:
   1) Regress A on B: compute α and β (hedge ratio — how many units of B match 1 unit of A)
   2) Compute residuals: ϵ = A − (α + β·B)
   3) Run ADF on residuals
   Interpretation: p < 0.05 = cointegrated (spread is stationary); p > 0.05 = not cointegrated

Direction B→A:
   Same procedure with A and B swapped.

Primary p-value for each quarter = the lower of the two direction p-values (stronger signal).
Pass condition per quarter: primary p-value < 0.05.


3. Output: 4 p-values, one per quarter

Report exactly four headline p-values — one per quarterly window:
   Q1 (oldest) : EG primary p-value  →  pass if p < 0.05  ✓ / ✗
   Q2          : EG primary p-value  →  pass if p < 0.05  ✓ / ✗
   Q3          : EG primary p-value  →  pass if p < 0.05  ✓ / ✗
   Q4 (recent) : EG primary p-value  →  pass if p < 0.05  ✓ / ✗

Also display both direction p-values (A→B and B→A) within each quarter card for transparency.

The pair passes the full cointegration test only if ALL FOUR quarters pass (4/4).
Report how many quarters passed (e.g. "2/4 quarters passed") even when the overall verdict is FAIL.
